  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reply
  author: Han Gyo-yeo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day of this month, the Envoy for Horizontal Proclamation and officials including Yeolyul-ui arrived bearing the imperial edict and command addressed to me. The command reads thus:

    "Some time ago, when the Jurchen showed disrespect, the Royal Army took up arms for their subjugation. Since last winter We have issued decrees commanding you to divide your forces and advance together. Though you reported your armies prepared, the enemy has not yet been eliminated. Now all forces have assembled and cross into their borders. Your troops, long since reviewed and ready, must advance without delay and coordinate with Us, lest you fall behind. We therefore send an official to observe your departure. Exert yourselves in loyal service and reverently obey these commands."

    The envoy came with urgent haste, his instructions severe and pointed. Receiving them with utmost respect, I know not what more to say.

    [In Reply]

    Your servant, dwelling in these remote island lands, has held his humble post as vassal, receiving the Emperor's great benevolence and dwelling long in peace under the royal way. Yet when winter came last year, suddenly a command descended from Heaven. Learning that the Jurchen troubled our Imperial Court, I resolved to support the heavenly punishment, relying upon the Emperor's sacred banner.

    I gathered my forces and marched toward the frontier, but the roads stretched long and treacherous, and the ice began to break. I was forced to withdraw and tend the fields, still training my troops. Unexpectedly, an envoy returned with gracious orders newly issued. Considering these kind commands with deepest reverence, I steel my heart anew.

    Yet I must confess: our lands are poor and our people impoverished. Our army grows weary and our strength diminishes—truly, this brings me shame. Though I cannot fully coordinate with the great campaign, I hope to render what small service I can toward its success. Without awaiting the imperial inspector's arrival, I have already dispatched my commanders and soldiers. We gather at the eastern frontier to block the bandits' passage, and guard the north against surprise attacks. Within the limits of our modest capacity, we hope to achieve some small merit. In this resolve, my humble sincerity burns ten thousand times stronger.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This appears to be a formal reply to an imperial edict regarding military operations against the Jurchen, likely from the Goryeo period when it was a tributary of the Khitan Liao dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The structure follows official court correspondence protocol: first the edict itself, then ''In Reply'' (中謝), where the vassal responds with expressions of respect, acknowledgment of limitations, and renewed commitment.'
